'''Shōichii''' ({{ill|Senior First Rank|ja|正一位}}) is one of the highest [[ranks]] in Japan's system of {{ill|Ritsuryō|ja|律令制}}-based hierarchy and {{ill|Shin’i|ja|神位}} (divine ranks). It ranks above {{ill|Jūichii|ja|従一位}}.
=== Overview === The rank of Shōichii has been historically conferred upon individuals who made extraordinary contributions to the state, such as {{ill|Kampaku|ja|関白}}, {{ill|Daijō Daijin|ja|太政大臣}}, or {{ill|Seii Taishōgun|ja|征夷大将軍}}. However, only seven individuals have ever received this rank during their lifetime.<ref group="注釈">These include {{ill|Fujiwara no Miyako|ja|藤原宮子}}, {{ill|Fujiwara no Muchimaro|ja|藤原武智麻呂}}, {{ill|Tachibana no Moroe|ja|橘諸兄}}, {{ill|Fujiwara no Nakamaro|ja|藤原仲麻呂}}, {{ill|Fujiwara no Nagate|ja|藤原永手}}, {{ill|Minamoto no Katako|ja|源方子}}, and {{ill|Sanetomi Sanjō|ja|三条実美}}. Two of these individuals, Fujiwara no Muchimaro and Sanetomi Sanjō, passed away on the same day they received the rank.</ref> Most instances of this rank were posthumously awarded as {{ill|Zōi|ja|贈位}}.
After {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新}}, the rank was formalized under the {{ill|Shokuinrei|ja|職員令}} of 1869.<ref>{{Egov law|215IO0000000325|位階令}}</ref> However, the rank became symbolic as the role's corresponding duties ceased to exist.
For {{ill|Shin’i|ja|神階}}, many shrines achieved the rank of Shōichii over time, particularly with the {{ill|Inari shrines|ja|稲荷神社}}, which adopted this rank after the main shrine, {{ill|Fushimi Inari Taisha|ja|伏見稲荷大社}}, received imperial recognition.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://inari.jp/about/history/num04/ |title=稲荷勧請 |publisher=伏見稲荷大社 |accessdate=2024-01-21}}</ref>
=== Shrines Awarded Shōichii === * {{ill|Kamo Shrine|ja|賀茂神社}} – 807 AD * {{ill|Katori Shrine|ja|香取神宮}} – 850 AD * {{ill|Kasuga Shrine|ja|春日神社}} * {{ill|Kashima Shrine|ja|鹿島神宮}} * {{ill|Hiyoshi Taisha|ja|日吉大社}}
=== Notable Individuals Awarded Shōichii === '''Bold''' indicates those awarded during their lifetime.
