ank--><!--Senior First Rank--><!--Senior First Rank-->

'''Shōichii''' ({{ill|Senior First Rank|ja|正一位|1=Senior First Rank|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) is one of the highest [[Court Ranks in Japan|Ranks]] in Japan's system of {{ill|Ritsuryō|ja|律令制|qq=draft|qq=draft}}-based hierarchy and [[Shinkai (divine rank)|Shinkai (divine Ranks)]]. It Ranks above {{ill|Junior First Rank|ja|従一位|1=Junior First Rank|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>https://www.wakapoetry.net/background/society/court-offices-titles-and-Ranks/court-Ranks/</ref>
== Overview == The Rank of Shōichii has been historically conferred upon individuals who made extraordinary contributions to the state, such as {{ill|Kampaku|ja|関白|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Daijō Daijin|ja|太政大臣|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, or {{ill|Shogun|ja|征夷大将軍|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. However, only seven individuals have ever received this Rank during their lifetime.<ref group="Note">These include {{ill|Fujiwara no Miyako|ja|藤原宮子|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Fujiwara no Muchimaro|ja|藤原武智麻呂|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Tachibana no Moroe|ja|橘諸兄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Fujiwara no Nakamaro|ja|藤原仲麻呂|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Fujiwara no Nagate|ja|藤原永手|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Minamoto no Katako|ja|源方子|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Sanetomi Sanjō|ja|三条実美|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Two of these individuals, Fujiwara no Muchimaro and Sanetomi Sanjō, passed away on the same day they received the Rank.</ref> Most instances of this Rank were posthumously awarded as {{ill|Zōi|ja|贈位|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
After {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the Rank was formalized under the {{ill|Shokuinrei|ja|職員令|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of 1869.<ref>{{Egov law|215IO0000000325|位階令}}</ref> However, the Rank became symbolic as the role's corresponding duties ceased to exist.
For {{ill|Shinkai (divine rank)|lt=Shin’i|ja|神階|1=Shinkai (divine rank)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, many shrines achieved the Rank of Shōichii over time, particularly with the {{ill|Inari shrines|ja|稲荷神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which adopted this Rank after the main shrine, {{ill|Fushimi Inari Taisha|ja|伏見稲荷大社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, received imperial recognition.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://inari.jp/about/history/num04/ |title=稲荷勧請 |publisher=伏見稲荷大社 |accessdate=2024-01-21}}</ref>
=== Shrines Awarded Shōichii === * {{ill|Kamo Shrine|ja|賀茂神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – 807 AD * {{ill|Katori Shrine|ja|香取神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – 850 AD * {{ill|Kasuga Shrine|ja|春日神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Kashima Shrine|ja|鹿島神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Hiyoshi Taisha|ja|日吉大社|1=Hiyoshi Taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
=== Notable Individuals Awarded Shōichii === '''Bold''' indicates those awarded during their lifetime.
{| class="wikitable" ! Name !! Date of Conferment !! Notes |- | {{ill|Fujiwara no Fuhito|ja|藤原不比等|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || {{ill|Yōrō|ja|養老|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 4 (720 AD) || Minister of the Right |- | '''{{ill|Fujiwara no Miyako|ja|藤原宮子|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' || {{ill|Shinkō|ja|神亀|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1 (724 AD) || Consort of Emperor Monmu |- | {{ill|Fujiwara no Nagate|ja|藤原永手|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || {{ill|Hōki|ja|宝亀|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1 (770 AD) || Minister of the Left |- | {{ill|Oda Nobunaga|ja|織田信長|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || {{ill|Taishō|ja|大正|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 6 (1917 AD) || Daimyō, posthumous award |}
